  "prompt": "How many colors and hues are distinguishable to the human eye?",
  "response": "The human eye can distinguish approximately 1 to 10 million different colors and hues. This variation is due to the complex interplay of light receptors in the retina, specifically the cones, which are sensitive to different wavelengths of light. \n\nIn terms of basic colors, most models of color perception suggest a common set of around 12 basic hues (including red, blue, green, yellow, etc.) that can be mixed in various ways to create the vast array of colors we perceive. However, the exact number of distinguishable colors can vary from person to person and can be influenced by factors such as lighting conditions, individual differences in vision, and color blindness.",
